🔐 Port and Attack Surface Report

All listed ports are configured as DENY IN (blocked for incoming traffic), which is a good security practice. However, it is still important to understand the risks associated with each service.

🌐 Web and Internet Services Ports
80/tcp – HTTP

Service: Web server (HTTP)
Common use: Websites without encryption

Common vulnerabilities:

SQL Injection (SQLi)
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
Directory traversal
Vulnerabilities in outdated web applications
443/tcp – HTTPS

Service: Secure web (TLS/SSL)
Common use: Secure websites

Common vulnerabilities:

TLS misconfiguration (weak ciphers)
Invalid/compromised certificates
Application-layer vulnerabilities (not HTTPS itself)
Downgrade attacks (on older systems)
📧 Email Services
25/tcp – SMTP

Service: Email sending

Common vulnerabilities:

Open relay (spam sending)
Sender spoofing
Bot abuse for spam
SMTP authentication flaws
🌍 DNS and Network Discovery
53/tcp – DNS

Service: Name resolution

Common vulnerabilities:

Cache poisoning
DDoS amplification
Improper zone transfer (AXFR)
Subdomain enumeration
5353/udp – mDNS (Multicast DNS)

Service: Automatic service discovery (Apple Bonjour, IoT)

Common vulnerabilities:

Local information leakage
Device spoofing on the network
Attacks on public Wi-Fi networks
1900/udp – SSDP / UPnP

Service: Device discovery (UPnP)

Common vulnerabilities:

DDoS amplification
Exposure of internal devices
Unauthorized remote control on misconfigured routers
🖥️ Remote Access
22/tcp – SSH

Service: Secure remote access

Common vulnerabilities:

Password brute force attacks
Poorly managed SSH keys
Weak credentials
Exploits in outdated versions
23/tcp – Telnet

Service: Unencrypted remote access

Common vulnerabilities:

Credential capture (cleartext)
Session hijacking
Common in insecure IoT devices
5900/tcp – VNC

Service: Graphical remote control

Common vulnerabilities:

Weak or default passwords
Unencrypted traffic (older versions)
Unauthorized remote access
📁 File Sharing
21/tcp – FTP

Service: File transfer

Common vulnerabilities:

Cleartext credentials
Anonymous login enabled
Malicious file uploads
FTP bounce attacks
445/tcp – SMB

Service: Windows file/printer sharing

Common vulnerabilities:

Remote code execution (RCE)
Ransomware propagation
Share enumeration
Historical flaws like EternalBlue
2049/tcp – NFS

Service: Linux file sharing

Common vulnerabilities:

Misconfigured exports (/etc/exports)
Unauthorized directory access
Privilege escalation via insecure mounts
🗄️ Databases
3306/tcp – MySQL

Service: MySQL/MariaDB database

Common vulnerabilities:

Weak passwords
Unauthorized remote access
SQL injection (via applications)
Data dumping if exposed
5432/tcp – PostgreSQL

Service: PostgreSQL database

Common vulnerabilities:

Misconfigured authentication
Unnecessary public exposure
Exploitation via unsafe extensions
6379/tcp – Redis

Service: Cache/NoSQL database

Common vulnerabilities:

Unauthenticated instances
File system write access (in older configs)
Remote system control via persistence tricks
27017/tcp – MongoDB

Service: MongoDB NoSQL database

Common vulnerabilities:

No authentication in older versions
Sensitive data exposure
Public database dumps on the internet
⚙️ System Services
111/tcp – rpcbind

Service: RPC service mapper (Linux)

Common vulnerabilities:

NFS service enumeration
Misconfigured RPC attacks
Internal service information leakage
🧠 Security Summary

Even with all ports blocked inbound:

🔒 You have significantly reduced the external attack surface
⚠️ Real risk also depends on:

Locally running services
Outbound firewall rules
Internal service configuration
System updates
🛡️ Quick Recommendations
Disable unused services (especially Telnet, FTP, SMB if not needed)
Use SSH with keys (no passwords)
Avoid exposing databases publicly
Monitor connection attempt logs
Keep all services updated
